Aratus

Target IP: 10.10.76.154
Challenge Description: Do you like reading? Do you like to go through tons of text? Aratus has what you need!

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.76.154 -p- -Pn returns the result shown above. By the looks of it, there are six TCP ports open. These applications are FTP, SSH, HTTP, HTTPs, and SMB. I will perform an aggressive scan against these open TCP ports to identify its application & services now.

I performed an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.76.154 -p 21,22,80,139,443,445 and obtained the result shown above. From the scan above, the FTP is open and it allows anonymous login. There is one directory with the name pub. Are there any files that I can access inside that directory? Can I upload files to that directory too? There is an SSH application open too on port 22. However, I do not have any credentials. The HTTP and HTTPs applications on port 80 and 443 are interesting too. However, the SMB would be the first place to check out to me; therefore, I will begin my enumeration here.

Enumeration

Ports 139 and 445: SMB

I decided to check the SMB shares on the target machine by running the command smbmap -u "" -p "" -H 10.10.76.154 first and obtained the result shown above. There is an interesting share with the name temporary share with READ ONLY permission. Time to connect to this share and see what is available.


I connected to the temporary share SMB by running the command smbclient //10.10.76.154/"temporary share" and gained access, as shown above. I notice the file message-to-simeon.txt. This file stands out to me the most. I downloaded this text file by running the command get message-to-simeon.txt.


Inside the message-to-simeon.txt text file, the message shown above is stored. There are two usernames that stand out to me: simeon and theodore. This text file mentions the user simeon is using a weak password and their home directory is in mess. Are there any more users? And what are the different directories with the names such as chapter1?


I created a directory with the name files on my machine. Then I started a new shell session and connected to the SMB on the target machine by running the command smbclient //10.10.76.154/"temporary share". To download all the contents inside these directories, I ran the commands in order:RECURSE ON first, prompt OFF, and finally mget *.


I checked the different files inside the directories individually. Most of these files were useless, until I found the crucial information shown above. The text file text2.txt inside chapter7 of paragraph7.1 contains some sort of encrypted RSA SSH key. Who does this belong to? Time to crack the passphrase and attempt to login with the different usernames.


I copied the RSA SSH key to a file called id_rsa on my machine. Then I changed the permission of the file to be private using the command chmod 400 id_rsa. Then I used the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash to obtain the hash of the passphrase from the SSH key. And finally, I executed the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt to bruteforce the passphrase testing123 of the SSH key.

Exploitation

Foothold: SSH via SSH Key of Simeon

I gained a foothold on the target machine by running the command ssh simeon@10.10.76.154 -i id_rsa and the passphrase testing123, as shown above. Now I have a foothold on the target machine as the user simeon, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: Simeon to Theodore

After gaining the foothold, I browsed /opt to check for any useful files as mentioned in the previous enumeration. But I did not find anything. This user's home directory is complete mess. When checking for capabilities set using the command getcap -r / 2>/dev/null returns the interesting entries above. The last two entries stand out to me the most. When running suexec, it mentions permissions denied. However, I am able to successfully execute tcpdump. This application can be used to listen to network traffic and capture any packets. Since there are FTP and HTTP applications running on the target machine, can I sniff these packets? Both of these applications are not encrypted protocols. Therefore, the network traffic is sniffable and readable. I ran the command tcpdump -i any tcp port 21 -vv to sniff any FTP network traffic, but there was nothing. However, the HTTP was different.


I ran the command tcpdump -i any tcp port 80 -vv and obtained the result shown above. When checking the Authorization header of one of the network packet, I obtained the base64 string dGhlb2RvcmU6UmlqeWFzd2FoZWJjZWliYXJqaWs= as shown above. Time to decode this string.


I decoded the base64 string using the command openssl enc -base64 -d <<< dGhlb2RvcmU6UmlqeWFzd2FoZWJjZWliYXJqaWs= and obtained the string theodore:Rijyaswahebceibarjik. This looks like a set of credentials. Is this the password of the user theodore? When switching to the user theodore by running the command su theodore and the password Rijyaswahebceibarjik, I managed to gain access. I have successfully elevated my privileges horizontally from the user simeon to theodore, as shown above.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: Theodore to Root

Running the command sudo -l shows the interesting information above. The script /opt/scripts/infra_as_code.sh can be executed as the user automation without password. What does this script perform?


Running the command cat /opt/scripts/infra_as_code.sh shows the script is responsible for running ansible-playbook on some yaml files. Can I edit these files? I am unable to edit these files when checking the permissions of these files by using the command ls -la /opt/ansible/playbooks/. Time to run the command sudo -u automation /opt/scripts/infra_as_code.sh to see what it does.


When I ran the script, I notice two more yml files that are executed by infra_as_code.sh script. These files are located at /opt/ansible/roles/geerlingguy.apache/tasks/configure-RedHat.yml and /opt/ansible/roles/geerlingguy.apache/tasks/setup-RedHat.yml as shown above.


I checked the possible yml files that I could change and found configure-RedHat.yml is possible, as shown above.


Checking the script content shows there is a part called command. Can I replace this line with my own command to open a root shell? I notice some conditions are set using the when command. I will need to remove this.


I created a new reverse shell script with the name shell.sh. This script invokes a reverse shell connection to my machine at port 8443, as shown above.


I ran vim and made the edits shown above on the file configure-RedHat.yml. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I used the command sudo -u automation /opt/scripts/infra_as_code.sh to execute the script.


And bingo. Now I have a root shell on the target machine :) I managed to successfully obtain a reverse shell connection from the target machine. GG.
